While $TSLA sales are only $21 billion as of now, analysts expect $TSLA to hit revenues of about $1 Trillion by 2030 (Ron Baron - Baron Funds). This is why companies like $TSLA $SHOP et al are “growth stocks”. They look highly valued if you follow conventional methods. >

Note $TSLA P/E ratio is also absurdly high. Conventional wisdom would tell you to sell your shares and wait for a pullback. However, conventional methods don’t always work. What they don’t take into account is $TSLA Total Addressable Market (TAM). >

This is known as the Price-to-Sales (P/S) ratio. What it means is that investors are willing to pay 25 times more than what a $TSLA share is worth in the books. While P/S ratios are not commonly used (P/E ratios are preferred), any P/S ratio over 3X is considered risky.

Bar graph below shows you $TSLA quarterly (Q) revenue growth over the last 5 years. As you may note, third quarter (3Q) and 4Q are normally when they generate most sales. In 2020, until end of 3Q, Tesla’s total revenue ~ $21 billion. Let’s say TSLA hits $11 billion in 4Q. > https://t.co/gPZan1SBdC
